1
00:00:03,700 --> 00:00:06,681
Shelley’s poem
called “Ozymandias”,

2
00:00:06,681 --> 00:00:12,053
which is about one of the kings 
of ancient Egypt,

3
00:00:12,053 --> 00:00:15,737
whether it’s Ramses I, II or III
or any one of them, it doesn’t matter.

4
00:00:15,934 --> 00:00:19,864
[No More Moscow, New York, Paris, London …]

5
00:00:19,874 --> 00:00:22,461
And in the poem, 
it is very simple,

6
00:00:22,461 --> 00:00:27,609
but a man, he’s saying,
“I met a traveler from an ancient land,

7
00:00:27,609 --> 00:00:32,352
and he told me of this very peculiar,
extraordinary occurrence

8
00:00:32,352 --> 00:00:43,522
that out in the middle of the desert
he saw a broken statue.”

9
00:00:43,527 --> 00:00:46,579
Like, from the waist here
it’s just broken.

10
00:00:46,619 --> 00:00:49,690
The head lying in one place, 
this part—in another,

11
00:00:49,700 --> 00:00:52,550
but then from here down 
and the legs.

12
00:00:52,564 --> 00:00:56,016
And then there’s an inscription 
upon the bottom, the base.

13
00:00:56,016 --> 00:01:02,067
And it says, “I am Ozymandius, 
King of the world,

14
00:01:02,067 --> 00:01:05,477
look upon my kingdom!”
 

15
00:01:06,657 --> 00:01:07,585
And he said,

16
00:01:07,585 --> 00:01:13,615
“But you see the head broke off, 
the arms are broken,

17
00:01:13,615 --> 00:01:19,075
and the head lying in the sand
has got this arrogant look.”

18
00:01:19,076 --> 00:01:21,729
He said, “Whoever sculpted it 
did a very good job 
 

19
00:01:21,729 --> 00:01:25,169
of conveying the arrogance 
of this man.”

20
00:01:25,169 --> 00:01:29,551
But when it says, 
“Look upon my kingdom!”

21
00:01:29,551 --> 00:01:31,334
And he said, 
“All you can see

22
00:01:31,334 --> 00:01:33,794
in all directions 
are the desert sand.”

23
00:01:33,794 --> 00:01:36,094
“There is no kingdom.”

24
00:01:36,094 --> 00:01:38,144
bhūtvā bhūtvā pralīyate 
[Bg: 8.19]

25
00:01:38,149 --> 00:01:41,379
Again, the whole world …
what to speak of that kingdom?

26
00:01:41,379 --> 00:01:44,861
Everything appears, 
the whole Universe appears,

27
00:01:44,861 --> 00:01:48,751
and then it vanishes 
along with everything in it.

28
00:01:49,233 --> 00:01:52,713
Like, Prabhupād would talk 
about the cosmonaut

29
00:01:52,713 --> 00:01:55,713
who was in space too long,

30
00:01:55,713 --> 00:01:59,602
and he kept asking them,
“Where is Moscow?”

31
00:01:59,602 --> 00:02:01,082
[Laughing]

32
00:02:01,082 --> 00:02:06,002
He wanted to look out:
“Where is Moscow?”

33
00:02:06,005 --> 00:02:17,115
No more Moscow, no more New York,
Paris, London … [Laughing]

34
00:02:17,115 --> 00:02:21,610
It appears and then it vanishes.
So Guru Mahārāj said,

35
00:02:21,610 --> 00:02:28,860
“That self we want to connect to 
and should, it’s living in eternity.”

36
00:02:28,860 --> 00:02:30,538
He’s saying, 
“Try and take your stand

37
00:02:30,538 --> 00:02:36,108
in the faithful world, 
in the faithful plane.”

38
00:02:36,938 --> 00:02:41,567
But that ‘muktir hitvānyathā rūpaṁ 
svarūpeṇa vyavasthitiḥ’ [SB: 2.10.6]

39
00:02:41,567 --> 00:02:45,557
is an identity that is capable 
of growth and development.

